            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Use the $5,000 Rule: Multiply system age by repair cost. If result exceeds $5,000, replacement typically makes better financial sense. Example: 10-year-old system needing $700 repair = 10 x 700 = $7,000, suggesting replacement. Additional replacement indicators include system age 12-15+ years (approaching average desert lifespan), refrigerant type R-22 (obsolete, expensive, system can't be upgraded to modern refrigerant), major component failure (compressor, air handler) costing $1,800+, recurring repairs requiring service calls multiple times yearly, dramatically increasing electric bills despite maintenance, and uneven cooling or humidity problems indicating system inadequacy. Repair makes sense when system under 8 years old, repair cost under $800, single isolated failure with otherwise reliable operation, and system properly sized and performing well when working. [link:/services/ac-replacement|Free replacement consultations] help determine best value for your situation including repair versus replacement analysis, proper system sizing and selection, financing options, and utility rebate coordination."
